### 1. Compound allocation chain in `FixedNumberOfWordsTruncator` (4+ allocs/call)
**🔴 Critical** — this is on the hot path per the user's description

**Impact:** Every call allocates a `string[]` from `Split`, a LINQ enumerator from `Take`/`Skip`, an intermediate string from `string.Join`, and another from `+` concatenation — **4+ heap allocations per truncation**.

**Files:** `Truncation.cs:L178, L187, L190`

**Fix:** Replace `Split` + LINQ with a single-pass word-counting loop using spans, then use `string.Concat` with spans for the final result.

```csharp
// Before (L178-190):
var words = value.Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
if (words.Length <= length) return value;
if (truncateFrom == TruncateFrom.Right)
    return string.Join(" ", words.Take(length)) + truncationString;
return truncationString + string.Join(" ", words.Skip(words.Length - length));

// After — zero-LINQ, single-pass approach:
int wordCount = 0;
int boundaryIndex = -1;
bool inWord = false;

if (truncateFrom == TruncateFrom.Right)
{
    for (int i = 0; i < value.Length; i++)
    {
        if (value[i] != ' ') { if (!inWord) { wordCount++; inWord = true; } }
        else
        {
            if (inWord && wordCount == length) { boundaryIndex = i; break; }
            inWord = false;
        }
    }
    if (boundaryIndex == -1 && wordCount <= length) return value;
    if (boundaryIndex == -1) boundaryIndex = value.Length;
    return string.Concat(value.AsSpan(0, boundaryIndex).TrimEnd(), truncationString.AsSpan());
}
// Mirror logic for Left using reverse scan
```

